{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_gabardine_ver01/data/sn87065167/00199916804/1908060101/0583.xml":{"full_text":"rv\n\nE\nNEWS\nEvery Inch\n..A NEWSPAPER..\nw\nHATTIESBURG. MISSISSIPPI MONDAY AFfERNOON JUNE 1. 1908\nVOL II. NO 12\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nit-'\n\nLast of the Goverment Attaches\nSent to Relieve Storm Suffer\ners Left Last Night.\nRED CROSS NURSES\nARE ALSO RELIEVED\niMajor Simpson Closing His Accounts\nToday\u2014Lets Than $60,000 of the\nGovernment Appropriation Hat Been\nUsed.\nWhen the people of Hattiesburg\nheard on April 24 that the flying\nclouds which passed with such speed\nover their beautiful city, were nothing\nless than a dreadful cyclone, there was\nt naturally a sigh of relief at the thought\nthat we had escaped its fury. This\nfact doubtless intensified the Interest\nfelt by everyone when it was learned\nthat our neighboring little city of Pur\nvis was practically destroyed.\nWith commendable promptness the\nNew Orleans and Northeastern Rail\nroad Company placed at the service\nof qpr city a train to be used In con\nveying relief to Purvis and for bring\ning the wounded to Hattiesburg. Near\nly every physician in our city with\nhundreds of our people boarded this\ntrain. On their arrival gt Purvis\neverything possible was done to care\nfor the dead and wounded, two hun\ndred or more of the latter were\nbrought to Hattiesburg at once, where\nfrom that moment they received every\nf\u00a3 -attention needed for their comfort and\n^^ftlfare. Never was there a more prac\n^WTcal demonstration of the broad sym\npathy men feel for their fellows when\nIn trouble than waa, given by this oc\ncasion.\nMen, womefl and even children\nseemed to vie with each other in their\nefforts to show sympathy and render\naid. We are quite sure there has not\nbeen a case since the days of-slavery\nof the negro, when racial lines were so\nnearly obliterated as in thls instanee.\nWe are sure not one negro natlent\nwould say that anything but the great\nest kindness and largest liberality was\nshown him. This fact applies as\nwell to the work of the local committee\nas to that of the government and of the\nRed Cross.\nWhen the conditions became gener\nally known our congressman. Eaton J.\nBowers, at once took up with his usual\npromptness and energy the question of\ngovernment aid. Congress at once au\nthorized the secretary of war to render\nsuch aid as was found necessary and\nMwijfiter made an appropriation of $250,000\n5 'for carrying out this work. Captain N.\nT. McLean, past assistant surgeon\nLasted Sinteaknavy at once came on\nthe ground and to his valuable aid and\nsuggestion much credit Is due for the\nfuture effective plans of relief that\nwere so promptly inaugurated by Maj.\nC. A. Duval, and later carried out with\nA\nBally News Special.\n^Rickson, Miss., June 1.\u2014Governor\nPool Is growing suspicious at the num\nber of social clubs being organized\nthroughout the state, and evidently\nsmells a mouse which leads him to\nsuspect that there might be .a locker or\nbuffet attached to a good many of\nthose who ard sending In charters for\nbis approval.\nWhile the Governor has not signified\nons in tha matter, It Is\nhi\u00ae\nsuch consummate skill and wisdom by\nMaj. Wlndell L. Simpson, of the\nUnited States army, ably assisted by\nMaj. B. K. Ashford, chief medical of\nflver and his efficient co-laborer, Lieut.\nHoward H. Bailey. In addition to the\ngovernment officials named, Dr. H. R.\nHermish, of the United Stales navy,\nand Dr. Chamberlain, of the army, both\nrendered very Intelligent service In the\nearly days of the relief work.\nThe closing of this work of govern\nment relief is now at band. Maj. Simp\nson, Dr. Ashford and Dr. Bailey all\nleave Wednesday night for their re\nspective posts of duty.\nNever, perhaps. In the history of ex\ntensive relief has there been shown\nsuch fidelity on the part of those en\ntrusted with the execution of the plans\nas In this case. Perfect harmony has\nprevailed between the government of\nficials and all of the relief committees.\nThese have worked together with the\ncommon end of rendering all aid\nneeded.\nThe entire hospital corps left last\nnight as did the Red Cross nurses.\nMajor Simpson Is closing his accounts\ntoday, all purchases having ceased\nSaturday. It will be a matter of strik\ning interest to note that perhaps not\nexceeding $60,000 of the government\nappropriation of $250,000 was used In\nthe states of Louisiana. Mississippi,\nAlabama and Georgia.\nSIMPLE LIFE\nJUST LISTEN\nHearst News Service.\nNew York, June 1.\u2014A simple life\ncolony, with children going naked and\nmen pledged to never cut their beards,\nwill start this fall near Vera Cruse,\nMexico, according to Gustave Andre, a\nsocialist leader of this city, who Is to\nbe at the head of the enterprise.\nMRS. ALBAUGH DEAD.\nHears* News Service.\nLong Beach, N. Y\u201e June 1.\u2014Mrs.\nMary Albaugh, ^lfe of the famous Bal\ntimore theatrical manager, died here\ntoday at the age of 74 years.\nGIRL HAH GONE\nTO NEW ORLEANS\nFOR TREATMENT\nLillian Hawley, the little girl who\nwas bitten by a mad dog, was carried\nto New Orleans Saturday night to take\nthe Pasteur-treatment\nOnly $19.25 has been received to pay\nthe expenses'of this child whose par\nents are poor. If there was ever a case\nthat called for charity this Is\nthose who want to help can leave their\nsubscriptions at Powe's Drug.Store.\none.\nknown that he is Investigating the\nmoral standing of some of the Incor\nporators, and In some cases It is be\nOleved he will turn the charters down\nentirely, or insert amendments which\nwill prevent the keeping of liquors\non. the premises,\nOne of the things that lead to these\nsuspicions Is the number of these\ncharters which are coming from tbs\ntown# which now have saloons, hut\nwhich will lie dry like the rest after\nthe first of January.\n\n\nRed Star Liner Believed to Have\nBeen Wrecked Show* Up at\nFlushing Today.\nHearst News Service.\nNew York, June 1.\u2014Cables received\nhere today report the Red star line\nship Baderland safe. The vessel passed\nFlushing, Holland, early this morning\nwith all on board well. A dense fog\ncaused several hours' delay and the\nvessel was tossed for hours on a rough\nsea, but tjiero Was no collision as re\nported in yesterday's dispatches.\nCOMMITTEES\nKnights of Pythias Plan Campaign\nFor 2,000 New Members\nDuring the Year.\nDaily News Special.\nJackson, Hiss., June 1.\u2014Hon. Will\nA. Sessions, of this city, who was re\ncently elected grand chancellor of the\nMississippi Grand Lodge, Knights of\nPythias at the^ickahurg meeting, has\nannounced his determination to se\ncure at least 2,000 new members In\nthe state within the next year, and to\nthat end has offered a number of\nprizes to local lodges which bring up\nthe best Bhowing in the way of .new\nmembership.\nIn accordance with the custom of\nThe order, Mr. Sessions has appointed\nthe standing committees for the next\nyear as follows:\nJudiciary\u2014L. J. Adler, Vicksburg;\nC. C. Dunn, Meridian; V. OtiB Robert\nson, Jackson.\nFinance\u2014Edward Yerger, Jackson;-J.\nR. Kelley, Gulfport; John M. Eddlns,\nByhalia.\nMileage and Per D(em\u2014J. D. Robert\nson, Friars Point; H. L. DuBard, Gren\nada; J. D. Clark, Scranton.\nCredentials\u2014A. L. Smith, Columbia;\nH. L. Morrison, Okolona; B. A. Lin\ncoln, Columbus.\nWays and Means\u2014J. M. Johnson,\nClarksdale; M. E. Morehead, LUmber\nton; J. H. Dunn, Mt. Olive.\nThe first committeeman named has\nbeen designated as chairman In each\ncase.\nIn addition tc the above, a special\ncommittee to organize military depart\nments has been appointed, composed\nof Sam Montgomery, chairman, Green\nville; R. Whitaker, Centrevllle, and J.\nO. Fuller, Jackson.\nTAFT FEARS\nFOR FUTURE\nFat Secretary Realizes That He\nHas Fight On HU Hands to\nDefeat Bryan. Va\nHearst News Service.\nNew York, June 1.\u2014Taft Is sure to\nbe the Republican nominee according\nto Senator Stone, who is also positive\nthat Bryan will lead Jj>e Democracy.\nSenator Stone also expressed the\nopinion that-Taft realizes the tact that'\nhe has a bard fight on his hands to de\nfeat Bryan,\nQUEEN WILBEMINA\nDINES DAVID HILL\nHearst News Service.\nThe Hague, 'June 1.\u2014Queen Wilhe\nmina dined Minister David Ja^ne HU]\nand wife In the Palace today and ex\npressed regret st their departufs. Y'^-1\n\nr.Xiife\n\nm\nit\nVA\n\nM\nWt:\nNl/i\nK|(Wo\nHi\ny\nf\nJ i\nV\n1/\nUiM'A\nii\n6 L\n7f 3\nt\nU\n11\nm\n\nF\nS\nSENATOR BURROWS. WHO WILL MAKE THE KEYNOTE SPEECH\nAT CHICAGO.\nSenator Julitls Oaesar Burrowa of Michigan, wbo bas been selected to act\nas temporary chairman at the Republican mtlonnl convention, will make the\nkeynote speech which will open the actual presidential cainpnlgn. While the\nsenator Is regarded as a conservative, hla course has been mainly In accord\nwltb the policies of Presldeul Roosevelt. Senator Burrows wns In the Forty\nninth, Fiftieth, Fifty-first. Fifty-second. Fifty-third and Fifty-fourth con\ngrosses and resigned In 1895 to succeed the late Seuator Stock bridge,\nwas re-elected In 1899 and again In 1905 On the latter occasion bis great pop\nularlty was attested when be received the vote of every member of the legls\nIn tore.\nHr\nNew York, June 1.\u2014Two were\nstantly killed and two others will die\nIn an auto-speeding contest oh Coney I\nHearst News Service.\nBRYAN SAFE\nSAYS HERALD\nt\nIlcarst News Service.\nNew York, June 1.\u2014In its political\nforecast today-the New York Herald\ngives'Bryan a total'Instructed vote of\n770 votes at the national Democratic\nconvention and.says that Bryan will go\nwithin 89 of the necessary two-thtrds\nmajority on the first ballot.\nBryan made a clean sweep last week,\nGray and Johnson standing attll.\nCOUNTING VOTE\nIN NEW YORK CITY\n\nNew York, June 1.\u2014Four boxes a\nday will be counted hereafter In the\nrecount of the votes ''xst for Hearst\nand McClellan In the race for mayor.\nHearst la still gaining in the recount\nand It Is believed that he will be\nproven the winner.\nTHE DAILY NEWS\nPROGNOSTICATOR\ntm\nSy\nWashington, June 1.\u2014Partly cloudy\npossibly showers tonight or Tuesday.\nv. I;.-\nIsland. The dead are Wm. P. Gou\nln-|beaud and Thomas Nolan. The auto\nswerved from, the regular course and\nI smashed against a tree.\nBOV BANDITS\nBOB EXPRESS\n_<S\nHearst News Service.\nGreat Falls, Mont., June 1.\u2014Four\nknee-breeches boy bandits held up and\nrobbed the Great Northern Railroad\nexpress here last night. One man was\nseriously shot by the robbers. The\nboys have been captured.\nT\nCHANCERY COURT\nHAS CONVENED\nChancery court convened at 2 o'clock\nthis afternoon, Judge Wood, of Gulf\nport, presiding.\nIt is -believed that the term will not\nlast longer than tJHa week, although\nlt_ can\nfound necessary to do se.\nSeveral rather important cases will\ncome up during the term and It is said\nthat the docket Is rather larger than\nusual.\nthrough nextVeek If it is\nJMARGIS TRIAL\nstarts slow\n\nMother of Yonng Man Who Killed\nFather Will Spent Fortune to\nSave His Neck.\nHearst News Service.\nLexfnftton, Ky., June L\u2014The trial of\nBeach Hargis for the murder of his\nJames Hargis, famous\nfeudist, was started today\nThe\nJ\nat Jackson, Breathitt County,\nfirst 100 men from which to select a\njnry have been summoned, but K Is\n\u25a0jits**\n\u20223\nCITY PRIMARIES WILL\nBE HELD JULY 22-29\n\u25a0o\n\u25a0o\nthought that Beveral days will elapse\nbefore the panel can be completed.\nYoung Hargis Is represented by the\nablest counsel which it Is possible to\nsecure, but the line of defense has not\nyet been announced. The mother of\ntile young man announced several\nweeks ago that she would spend $50,\n000 if necessary to save the life of her\nboy.\nA FINE PROGRAM\nFOR TOMORROW\nTomorrow, June 2, the\nNormal wlU open at the South Missis\nsippi College and continue until the\nlatter part of the month. A competent\ncorps of Instructors has been secured\nand a large attendance Is expected.\nThe first day's program (tomorrow) Is\nof general interest and a large crowd\nIs expected.\nTuesday Morning, at 11 O'clock.\nInvocation\u2014Rev. J. N. McMillin.\nPiano Solo\u2014Miss Anna Belle Mc\nCarty.\nWelcome Address on Part of City\u2014\nDr. Donald.\nWelcome Address on part of City\nand County\u2014Superintendents Currie\nand Woodley.\nSelection by-college quartette.\nThe Scope and Purpose of Normal\nProf. Thames.\nAnnouncement by Prof. H. P. Todd,\ndirector.\nTeachers'\nAt 8:30 P. M.\nMemorial Exercises\u2014Capt. J. P. Car\nterf presiding.\nAddress by Hon. J. R. Tally.\nMusical program now being\nranged.\nPublic cordially invited.\nar\nARE AT MK\nEnd of the Financial Panic Here\nSay Merchants, Bankers\nand Financiers.\nHearst News Service.\nSt. Louis, June 1.\u2014Actual figures se\ncured today by officers of the Prosper\nity Association show that 17,000 Idle\nmen returned to work in this city to\nday.\nAT BIRMINGHAM.\nBirmingham, Ala.? June 1.\u2014Two\nthousand miners and as many furnace\nmen returtied to work this morning\nIt Is estimated that the railroads will\nput on 5;000 more during the week.\nBankers, merchants and financiers say\nthat the panic Is over In this district\nfor good.\nONE NEGRO KILLS ANOTHER.\nNews has reached here from Ellis\nvllle that a difficulty occurred there\nyesterday between two negroes, Steve\nI-ang and Arthur Coleman,-* In which\nLang was shot and killed.\nALL ARE EMPLOYED\nBIRMINGHAM\n\n\nMr. Sid Smith, a prominent railroad\ncontractor of Birmingham, ls^ln the\ncity today, having-come hei\nteams for the purpose of ul\nbuy ox\nlng them to\nrork between\nhaul logs on railroad\nMemphis and Binning)\nIn speaking ot JJrte conditions that\nprevail In the\nwhich was bad\n(am.\nllrmiugham district,\nhit by the financial\n-r\nCity Executive Committee Met\nCity Hall This Morning\nand Reorganized.\nat\nALL MEMBERS WERE\nPRESENT EXCEPT ONE\nDecided to Have Early Primaries.\nMust Register Before July 12 to Be\na Qualified Voter in the City\nPrimaries.\nThe City Democratic Executive C(\nmittee met in the city hall this\nlng, with all the members present,\ncept Mr. Draughn, including the\nand the new members.\nMr. J. K. Denham was elected,\nmember of the committee to fill a\ncancy that existed on the old cl\nmittee.\nme\nMr. W. M. Conner was elected ei)\nman, and A. H. McSwain secretar;\nA motion was made and carried t\nthe date for the first primary be set)\nWednesday, July 22, and that the\nof the second primary be fixed\nJuly 2$\u2014seven\nWednesday,\nlater.\nThe chairman was instructed to\npoint a committee to revise the\nbooks. This committee will be\nnounced later.\nOfficers to hold the election\nappointed.\nPoll books will he closed, so faj\nthis ejection Is concerned, on July!\nAll who desire to participate must\nster before that date.\nThe committee will hold ano)\nmeeting June 20 to enroll nann-i\ncandidates and j>ro rate the expeil\nKM\n.4)\nOUT DRIVING\nHearst News Service.\nPrinceton, N. J., June 1.\u2014Ex-PresI-\ndent Grover Cleveland went driving\nthis afternoon. His physicians have\nbeen dismissed and It is said that his\nhealth Is better than In many months.\nis\nRICHARDSON MAKES\nVIGOROUS PROTEST\n\n\nHearst- News Service.\nWashington, June 1.\u2014Congressman\nRichardson called on the President to\nday to protest against the appointment\nof Judge Hudley. 'The case was re-\u00bb\nferred to Attorney General Bonaparte.\n\u2022M\nA TEAPOT\nFour hundred years \"old will be on\nexhibition for the public at ten cents\nadmission fee.' G. K. Russ' store, West l<; 3\nPine street, 297.\nm\nrq\nGood Definition.\nA gentleman Is born with the neces\nsity of thinking of others before he\ndoes of himself.\u2014Florida Tlmes-Unlon.\ntrouble last fall,'Mr. Suilih said mat\nall the furnaces and mills In and\naround Birmingham had started opera\ntions and that there were, now no\nIdle people In the city. Everything\nwas on the move and the city was as\n-prosperous as It ever was. Railroad\nwork was picking up in Alabama and\nTennessee and he thought the financial\npanic was now a matter ot history.\nTV\nr","height":"17160","width":"14328"}}
